knowledge_graph.title: New Zealand Spinach
knowledge_graph.description: Tetragonia tetragonioides, commonly called New Zealand spinach, Warrigal greens and other local names, is a flowering plant in the fig-marigold family. It is often cultivated as a leafy vegetable. It is a widespread species, native to eastern Asia, Australia, and New Zealand.

related_questions.question: What is the difference between New Zealand spinach and regular spinach?
related_questions.snippet: New Zealand spinach is a warm season vegetable that grows well in hot weather and dry conditions. Regular spinach goes to seed and becomes bitter during warm summer months. Spinach also has many disease and pest problems, while New Zealand spinach is relatively pest and disease free.
related_questions.title: How to Grow New Zealand Spinach in Your Garden | USU

related_questions.question: Is New Zealand spinach a perennial or annual?
related_questions.snippet: The plant originates in New Zealand, Australia, and Asia and is considered a perennial in those warmer climates. Here in North America, it's grown as more of a tender annual, but depending on your zone, it could overwinter. Unlike spinach, which is more of a cool weather veggie, New Zealand spinach thrives in the heat.

related_questions.question: What is the taste of New Zealand spinach?
related_questions.snippet: New Zealand spinach has a mild, vegetal, and salty flavor suited for lightly cooked preparations, and young leaves are the preferred age for use in culinary dishes.
